 {"id": "franken_networkx-circself", "title": "REVIEW: [MEDIUM] circulant_graph rejected n=0 and silently dropped self-loops", "description": "nx.circulant_graph accepts n=0 (empty) and produces self-loops when an offset is divisible by n (e.g. n=1 with offset 1; n=2 with offset 2). The Rust binding rejected n=0 entirely and the fast path dropped self-loops, breaking parity. Fix: only delegate to Rust when n>=2 AND no offset is divisible by n; fall back to the Python path (which already emits correct self-loops) otherwise.", "status": "closed", "priority": 3, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T13:55:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T13:55:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T13:55:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Gate Rust path on self-loop-free case", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
 {"id": "franken_networkx-windvalid", "title": "REVIEW: [HIGH] windmill_graph silently accepted n<2 producing a malformed graph", "description": "nx.windmill_graph raises NetworkXError('A windmill graph must have at least two cliques') for n<2 and NetworkXError('The cliques must have at least two nodes') for k<2. fnx's wrapper delegated straight to Rust: windmill_graph(0, 3) returned a 1-node Graph and windmill_graph(1, 3) returned a 3-node triangle, neither of which is a windmill graph. Validate n<2 and k<2 with nx's exact wording so callers can't silently construct wrong graphs.", "status": "closed", "priority": 2, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T13:55:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T13:55:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T13:55:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Python-side validation with nx messages", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
 {"id": "franken_networkx-knesvalid", "title": "REVIEW: [MEDIUM] kneser_graph accepted n<=0 / k<=0 / k>n; nx rejects", "description": "nx.kneser_graph requires n>0 and 0<k<=n; rejects otherwise with NetworkXError. fnx accepted n=0 and k=0, producing a 1-node graph whose single node was the empty tuple (). Added the nx-compatible validation so invalid inputs raise the same message. Keeps k==n accepted (returns 1-node, 0-edge graph) as nx does.", "status": "closed", "priority": 3, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T13:55:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T13:55:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T13:55:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Python-side validation with nx messages", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
+{"id": "franken_networkx-shcomm", "title": "REVIEW: [HIGH] cn/ra_soundarajan_hopcroft silently computed on nodes without community attr", "description": "nx.cn_soundarajan_hopcroft and nx.ra_index_soundarajan_hopcroft raise NetworkXAlgorithmError('No community information available for Node X') when any node in ebunch lacks the community attribute. fnx treated missing community as None and silently computed a plain common-neighbor count (cn) or a wrong formula (ra, which also used (1+bonus)/deg(w) instead of nx's sum(1/deg(w) for w with community==Cu) conditional on Cu==Cv). Users expecting the strict contract would get wrong numbers without any signal. Fix: added _lp_community_of helper raising NetworkXAlgorithmError with nx's exact wording; rewrote ra formula to match nx exactly including int 0 early return when Cu!=Cv.", "status": "closed", "priority": 2, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T14:05:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T14:05:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T14:05:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Match nx contract + formula", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
+{"id": "franken_networkx-wicalgerr", "title": "REVIEW: [LOW] within_inter_cluster raised NetworkXError; nx raises NetworkXAlgorithmError", "description": "nx.within_inter_cluster raises NetworkXAlgorithmError('No community information available for Node X') when a node lacks the community attribute. fnx previously raised NetworkXError with a different message ('Set node attribute community first'). Callers catching the algorithm-error base class diverged. Fixed to raise the exact nx exception type + message.", "status": "closed", "priority": 4, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T14:05:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T14:05:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T14:05:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Use NetworkXAlgorithmError + nx message", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
+{"id": "franken_networkx-chaindec", "title": "REVIEW: [HIGH] chain_decomposition was a no-op on any cyclic graph", "description": "fnx.chain_decomposition delegated to a Rust binding that returned an empty iterator for every graph with cycles (triangle, K4-minus-edge, two-triangles, K4). Only trees produced correct (empty) output. Since chain_decomposition is a primitive for cycle-basis / 2-edge-connectivity work, any caller relying on it silently got wrong behavior. Fix: route through _call_networkx_for_parity so nx's reference DFS-based decomposition drives the output; all probed graphs now return non-empty chain lists that span the correct edge set.", "status": "closed", "priority": 2, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T14:05:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T14:05:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T14:05:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Delegate to nx reference impl", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
+{"id": "franken_networkx-smallrng", "title": "REVIEW: [MEDIUM] sigma/omega diverged from nx for same (G, seed, nrand)", "description": "nx.sigma and nx.omega use @py_random_state to obtain a stateful RNG that is threaded through all inner random_reference/lattice_reference calls, so each of the nrand iterations advances the RNG and consumes different reference graphs. fnx had its own local loop using Python stdlib Random and per-iteration seed derivation via rng.randint(0, 2**31), producing different numeric results for the same (G, seed, nrand) inputs. Delegated to nx via _call_networkx_for_parity; fnx still keeps the early type/size error-path checks (NetworkXNotImplemented on multigraph/directed, NetworkXError on <4 nodes) so the fast-fail behavior is unchanged.", "status": "closed", "priority": 3, "issue_type": "bug", "created_at": "2026-04-24T14:05:00.000000000Z", "created_by": "cc-networkx", "updated_at": "2026-04-24T14:05:00.000000000Z", "closed_at": "2026-04-24T14:05:00.000000000Z", "close_reason": "Delegate scalar computation to nx", "source_repo": ".", "compaction_level": 0, "original_size": 0}
